  "description": [
    "Plain Economics by John T Fiynn It is true to say that all of our past financial history has proved amply that the bankers influence in the management of industry has been bad almost beyond description NEW YORKMr William O Douglas of the Securities and Exchange Commission has stirred up a lot of pother around his valiant ears He made a speech before the Bond Club of New York which is in the very heart of Wallst which set many heads wagging The members of the Bond Club and Wallst generally have heard such proposals as Mr Douglas made before But they have come most fre quently from what waiist Ikes to think of as highly irresponsible per sons Mr Douglas however is high authority Not only does he usually know what he is talking about but he in a position of power What he said was that investment bankers whose business it is to pro vide funds for corporations thru the underwriting and sale of securities ought not be permitted to be part of the management of corporations and that corporations should let out their security issues to bankers on competitive bidding instead of giving them a monopoly of"
